[3]
Date: Tue 27 May 2003
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
Source: The Straits Times Interactive, Tue 27 May 2003 [edited]
<http://straitstimes.asia1.com.sg/singapore/story/0,4386,191323,00.html>

Singapore: Doubling in Number of Dengue Fever Cases
---------------------------------------------------
The hot weather and a cyclical change in the dominant strain of
dengue here could explain why doctors are seeing a doubling in the
number of cases this year. With 50 to 100 cases being reported
weekly, figures for the first half of this year are twice as high as
the same period last year, said SARS Combat Team Chief Khaw Boon Wan
on Sun 25 May 2003.
The National Environment Agency (NEA) stated that: "During an El Nino
period like the one we are in now, the warmer temperatures favour the
[multiplication] of the virus in mosquitoes. This efficient
[multiplication] translates into increased transmission of dengue
virus, as is evident in the increase in cases, not only in Singapore
but in many parts of the world. The number of dengue fever cases from
January to April [in 2003] -- 1601 -- is close to the 1786 cases for
the same period in 1998, when the El Nino effect was at its worst."
El Nino is a weather phenomenon caused by a build-up of warm surface
water in the Pacific Ocean, which affects wind direction and results
in hotter weather. For example, the average temperature this month is
28.8 deg C instead of the usual 28.2 deg C, said the Meteorological
Services Division.
Another possible reason for the recent rise in the number of
infections could be a change in the dominant strain [serotype?] of
dengue virus, suggested tropical medicine and infectious diseases
expert Oon Chong Teik.
He explained that 4 different [serotypes] of dengue virus exist, one
of which [may] become dominant at a point in time, and infect a
majority of people. Patients who are infected by one particular
strain develop an immunity to it after they recover, but they are
still vulnerable to the other strains. Every one to 3 years, for
unknown reasons, another strain [serotype?] of the virus becomes
dominant, and the number of cases then tends to increase sharply
because many people are not immune to it, he said.
The situation this year has been complicated by SARS, because both
viral diseases share some common symptoms -- high fever, body aches,
and in some cases, rashes. Most of the doctors interviewed said that
if patients do not have respiratory problems such as breathlessness
or a cough, or any SARS contact or travel history, they are unlikely
to have SARS.
Controlling the spread of dengue fever involves stopping mosquitoes
from breeding. NEA said: "The key to mosquito control is to remove
all stagnant water to deny the mosquitoes places to breed in." NEA
has intensified checks for breeding grounds.
[Byline: Lee Hui Chieh and Ken Lee]
