[4]
Date: Sat 31 May 2003
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source The Strait Times, Sat 31 May 2003 [edited]
<http://straitstimes.asia1.com.sg/singapore/story/0,4386,191896,00.html?>

Singapore: A total of 456 Cases Reported during May
---------------------------------------------------
The total number of cases [in 2003] is now 1842, with 456 being
reported [in May] alone. The situation is not likely to improve
within the next month, as the recent hot and dry spell favours the
[multiplication] of the virus in mosquitoes.
The worst affected area is Minbu Road/Mandalay Road in the Balestier
area, which has had 34 cases so far. It is one of 11 areas that have
been identified as 'active dengue clusters' by the National
Environment Agency (NEA). These are areas where 2 or more dengue
cases have occurred within a 200-meter radius.
The sudden surge in cases started 2 weeks ago when temperatures
soared. 96 new cases were reported between 11 and 17 May 2003. There
were 56 the previous week. Between 18 and 24 May, 127 cases were
reported. So far this week, there have been 114. Though the recent
number of cases is 4 times higher than the weekly average of 33 seen
between January and May 2002, they are not a cause for alarm, said Mr
Wang Nan Chee, director-general of public health at the NEA. There
were about the same number during an outbreak in July 2003, when an
average of 129 cases a week were reported until the end of September.
Mr Wang said 99.7 per cent of the cases here have been mild ones.
Only 0.3 per cent of those contracting the disease have been
officially classified as having dengue haemorrhagic fever, which
causes internal bleeding. However, 2 people died of it in January
2003, compared to none in 2002 and 4 in 2001.
To combat the dengue-carrying _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, the NEA will
carry out more inspections, visiting areas which are more prone to
mosquito breeding every [2 weeks] instead of once a month. For
example, landed properties in the East Coast and Serangoon Gardens
will be targeted.
