[5]
Date: Wed 28 May 2003
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
Source: Magnetic Times online, Wed 28 May 2003 [edited]
<http://magnetictimes.com/index.php?d=1&ID=716>

Australia: First Locally-acquired Case of Dengue Reported in Townsville
-------------------------------------------------
Queensland Health is urging all Townsville and Magnetic Island
residents to take responsibility for reducing mosquito numbers after
the first locally acquired case of dengue fever, for the year, was
reported in Townsville yesterday.
Dengue fever has gripped the far northern city of Cairns in recent
months, where the disease has affected up to 400 people. However,
Townsville and Magnetic Island have remained dengue fever-free since
May 2002. Mr Piispanen, Director of Environmental Health with the
Tropical Public Health Unit, told Magnetic Times that the patient
(from the Townsville suburb of Vincent) has had no recent travel
history, so it was likely the disease had been acquired in the
Townsville area.
"The outbreak was probably initiated when an infected person brought
in the virus either from overseas or possibly the Cairns area.
Unfortunately, it appears that there were also dengue mosquitos
present in the Vincent area at the time. Having bitten this infected
person, these mosquitos were then able to carry the virus, triggering
a local outbreak." said Mr Piispanen. Mr Piispanen went on to say
that it was vitally important that all residents and businesses take
responsibility for reducing mosquito numbers by cleaning up breeding
sites. "Residents should empty and store in a dry place, or dispose
of any containers such as tires, toys, pot plant bases, flower vases,
tarps, or backyard rubbish in which mosquitoes can breed. Check your
roof gutters to make sure they are not blocked with leaves" said Mr
Piispanen.
The dengue fever mosquito (_Aedes aegypti_) prefers to breed in small
receptacles; it also tends to bite people during the day that are
indoors rather than outdoors. Wearing loose, long, light-coloured
clothing and insect repellant will help stop the spread of the
disease.
