[6]
Date: Fri 30 May 2003
From: H.L. Penning <hlpenning@yahoo.com>
Source: cities.expressindia.com, Express News Service, Thu 29 May 2003 [edited]
<http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=53341>

India: First Dengue Case in Ahmedabad for 5 Years; Health Alert
-------------------------------------------------
With the admission of an 11-year-old to a city hospital with dengue
fever on Mon 26 May 2003, this disease has resurfaced in the city
after 5 years. The child, a resident of Jamalpur, was brought to
Medi-Surge hospital last Monday. He was diagnosed to be suffering
from secondary dengue shock syndrome. Dr Shabbir Momin, a consulting
physician who is handling the case, said, "He is fine now, as his
body temperature is normal. The child was brought to me with symptoms
of dengue infection. His body temperature was below normal, he had
fever in the recent past, his haemoglobin count was high and platelet
count was low," he added.
This is the first confirmed case in the last 5 years, said Dr P K
Makwana, the Ahmedabad Municipal Corporation (AMC) health officer.
However, with the monsoon round the corner, this case has made
Corporation officials pull up their socks and take action. AMC has
intensified its efforts to curb the [spread] of mosquitoes in the
city. AMC rushed a team of medical officials to Jamalpur to take
preventive measures like spraying [anti-larval] insecticides on
bodies of water. Besides, AMC officials also conducted a survey in
the area to determine whether any more persons showed signs of
dengue. So far no one has shown signs of having dengue.
Dengue is a viral infection [spread] by the mosquito _Aedes aegypti_,
which bites [humans] during the day. The incubation period of the
virus in the body is usually 5 to 10 days, said Dr Makwana. Signs
exhibited by a dengue patient are very similar to those of a malaria
patient. In the primary stage of dengue infection, the patient runs
high fever, body pain is acute, and rashes show up on the patient's
body. But in the secondary stage, the infection is fatal and care
needs to be taken to provide treatment to the patient in the first 48
hours, said Dr Momin.
--
